// Boating-licence question bank — GIFT export for Moodle.
// Self-contained: figures are embedded as base64 data URIs.

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Definitions

::q-oni-oniart142-d5cfcfd2-3672f8fd:: [html]According to ONI art. 142, which ordinance do the definitions of "risk analysis", "safety report" and "duty of diligence" refer to? {
=To the ordinance of 14 March 1994 on the construction of vessels (OCEB).
~To the Inland Navigation Ordinance (ONI) itself.
~To the Navigation Regulations for Lake Geneva (RNL).
####[html]ONI art. 142 refers, for these concepts, to the articles of the OCEB (ordinance of 14 March 1994 on the construction of vessels).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 142 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart142-d5cfcfd2-d09c7f3f:: [html]Among these statements about the definitions in ONI art. 142, which one is FALSE? {
=The "duty of diligence" is defined in ONI art. 142 without reference to another ordinance.
~The "safety report" is a report within the meaning of art. 2, let. e, and art. 17, para. 3, OCEB.
~The "expert examination report" is a report within the meaning of art. 2, let. f, OCEB.
####[html]According to ONI art. 142, let. e, the "duty of diligence" is defined by reference to art. 5 OCEB, and not without reference.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 142 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart142-d5cfcfd2-f9d06e2e:: [html]According to ONI art. 142, how are the "experts" defined within the meaning of the special provisions of this section? {
=As the persons referred to in art. 5a, para. 1, let. a, OCEB.
~As the officers of the competent authority of the place of mooring.
~As the members of a recognized classification society.
####[html]According to ONI art. 142, let. c, the "experts" are the persons referred to in art. 5a, para. 1, let. a, OCEB.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 142 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart2-2bf27aad-1ca80827:: [html]What is a “pushed convoy” according to the ONI? {
=An assembly of non-propelled vessels joined together into a rigid unit, pushed by at least one motorised vessel
~An assembly of non-propelled vessels towed by at least one motorised vessel
~Any group of pleasure craft navigating together
####[html]ONI art. 2\: the pushed convoy is a rigid unit that is pushed; if towed \= towed convoy.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 2 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart2-2bf27aad-de726c75:: [html]Within the meaning of the ONI, what does the term "motorized vessel" designate? {
=A vessel with mechanical propulsion
~A non-propelled vessel towed by another vessel
~A floating device such as a dredger or a crane
####[html]ONI art. 2\: a "motorized vessel" is a vessel with mechanical propulsion.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 2 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart71-ba2d9252-5d9ad386:: [html]According to RNL art. 71, does navigation in restricted visibility also concern situations that are not explicitly listed? {
=Yes, it also covers any other conditions limiting visibility in the same manner.
~No, only the conditions specifically cited (mist, fog, etc.) are covered.
~Yes, but only conditions caused by smoke from a fire.
####[html]RNL art. 71 extends the concept to any other conditions limiting visibility in the same manner.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 71 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart71-ba2d9252-ac555567:: [html]According to RNL art. 71, what is considered navigation in restricted visibility? {
=Any navigation, by day as by night, in mist, fog, drizzle, snow or heavy squalls with rain.
~Only navigation at night in thick fog.
~Only navigation by day when the rain is accompanied by strong wind.
####[html]RNL art. 71 defines restricted visibility as any navigation, by day as by night, in mist, fog, drizzle, snow or heavy squalls with rain.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 71 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart71-ba2d9252-b6ad0be5:: [html]Among these statements about restricted visibility within the meaning of RNL art. 71, which one is FALSE? {
=Navigation in restricted visibility applies only to navigation at night.
~Navigation in snowy weather is considered navigation in restricted visibility.
~Navigation in drizzly weather is considered navigation in restricted visibility.
####[html]RNL art. 71 states that restricted visibility applies both by day and by night, and not only at night.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 71 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Meteorology

::q-meteovents-météosuisselabise-22689f11-4b3bcbb4:: [html]Among these statements about la bise, which one is correct? {
=Its speed is between 3 and 9 Bf, and both its onset and its end are gradual.
~It arises abruptly, like the föhn, and always precedes rain.
~Summer bises last longer than winter ones.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: La bise, its speed ranges from 3 to 9 Bf, and its onset and end are gradual (unlike the föhn).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: La bise — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselabise-22689f11-b98b681a:: [html]Which pressure situation causes la bise to set in? {
=High pressure over the British Isles and low pressure over Italy.
~Low pressure over the British Isles and high pressure over Italy.
~High pressure over Italy and low pressure over Savoy.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: La bise, it sets in when high pressure covers the British Isles and low pressure covers Italy.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: La bise — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselabise-22689f11-ecb58b8d:: [html]During which period is the Bise clearly dominant on Lake Geneva? {
=In the first half of the year, particularly in spring
~In high summer, from July to August
~Only during autumn nights
####[html]MeteoSwiss\: the Bise is dominant in the first half of the year, especially in spring.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: La bise — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselavaudaire-f5cb790-37f5685c:: [html]Which statement is correct about the storm vaudaire? {
=It is cold\: as soon as it appears, the temperature drops and the humidity rises.
~It is warm and dry, raising the temperature as soon as it appears.
~It occurs exclusively from December to March.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: La vaudaire, the storm vaudaire is cold, with a drop in temperature and a rise in humidity as soon as it appears.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: La vaudaire — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselavaudaire-f5cb790-b505be53:: [html]Concerning the two types of vaudaire, which of these statements is FALSE? {
~The föhn vaudaire appears mainly in March-April as well as in October-November.
~The storm vaudaire appears from April to September.
=The föhn vaudaire is a cold, humid wind laden with precipitation.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: La vaudaire, the föhn vaudaire comes back down dried out and warmed after having shed its humidity on the southern side of the Alps.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: La vaudaire — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselebornan-d1fc474f-67c3a3ef:: [html]What are the warning signs that announce le Bornan? {
=The build-up of large cumulus and cumulonimbus clouds over the high ground, particularly the Savoy Prealps.
~A perfectly clear and stable sky above the Dent d'Oche.
~The appearance of a roll cloud bordering the Jura.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Le Bornan, the build-up of cumulus and cumulonimbus clouds over the high ground, especially the Savoy Prealps, is its warning sign.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Le Bornan — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselebornan-d1fc474f-ff8c6b5b:: [html]Which statements are correct about le Bornan? {
~%50%It can reach 30 to 40 kt and its effects are felt mainly between Rolle and Lutry.
~%50%It is one of the most violent storm winds of Lake Geneva, occurring in summer.
~%-100%It is a cold winter wind channelled by the Rhône valley.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Le Bornan, it reaches 30 to 40 kt between Rolle and Lutry and is one of the most violent summer storm winds of Lake Geneva.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Le Bornan — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselejoran-cd094d9d-5b912ce7:: [html]From which direction and origin does le joran come? {
=It is a NW wind, relatively cold, that comes down from the Jura towards Lake Geneva.
~It is a SE wind, warm, that comes up from the Rhône valley.
~It is a NE wind that blows from the Vaud Prealps.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Le joran, the joran is a relatively cold NW wind that comes down from the Jura towards Lake Geneva.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Le joran — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselejoran-cd094d9d-6ab55d25:: [html]How do the storm joran and the joran that rises after a cold front compare? {
=The storm joran is often dangerous because it is sudden and sometimes violent.
~The gusts of the cold-front joran are clearly stronger than those of the storm joran.
~The storm joran blows steadily and is appreciated by sailors.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Le joran, the storm joran is sudden and sometimes violent, hence often dangerous, unlike the steady cold-front joran.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Le joran — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselesbrises-7381ec08-0b097fc2:: [html]What is the origin of the alternating breezes observed near lakes? {
=The difference in temperature between the water, warmer at night, and the land, warmer during the day.
~The arrival of an Atlantic disturbance over Lake Geneva.
~The channelling of cold air coming down from the Jura.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Les brises, they originate from the difference in temperature between the water (warmer at night) and the land (warmer during the day).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Les brises — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselesbrises-7381ec08-44063844:: [html]Which statements are correct about daytime and nighttime breezes? {
~%50%Daytime breezes blow from the lake towards the shore.
~%50%Nighttime breezes generally rise between 5 and 7 p.m.
~%-100%Nighttime breezes blow from the shore towards the lake and are very violent winds.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Les brises, daytime breezes blow from the lake towards the shore and nighttime ones (weak winds) rise between 5 and 7 p.m.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Les brises — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-meteovents-météosuisselevent-4923b0ba-fc409519:: [html]Which weather situation does Le Vent (sudois) correspond to? {
=Low pressure over the British Isles and high pressure over southern Europe.
~High pressure over the British Isles and low pressure over southern Europe.
~A NE bise channelled between the Jura and the Prealps.
####[html]According to MétéoSuisse\: Le Vent, it corresponds to low pressure over the British Isles and high pressure over southern Europe.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.meteosuisse.admin.ch/portrait/meteosuisse-blog/fr/2023/05/les-vents-du-leman.html">MétéoSuisse \: Le Vent — MétéoSuisse — Les vents du Léman (Fri, 29 May 2026 19\:47\:39 GMT)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig61-729183ab-f8d636dd:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
~Boat landing area
~The width of the passage is limited
=Strong wind warning
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 61 — « Strong wind warning ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 61 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig62-4c0da81f-7b8892da:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
=Storm warning
~Dam
~Strong wind warning
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 62 — « Storm warning ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 62 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Navigation law

::q-oni-oniart134-df53e657-020997c6:: [html]What minimum buoyancy must individual lifesaving devices have according to ONI art. 134 (excluding the exception of art. 134a)? {
=At least 75 N.
~At least 100 N.
~At least 50 N.
####[html]ONI art. 134, al. 2 sets the buoyancy of individual devices at at least 75 N.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 134 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart134-df53e657-3d8f18d6:: [html]According to ONI art. 134, above which thresholds must a pleasure or sport boat be provided with an additional lifesaving device that can be thrown into the water? {
=A power output greater than 30 kW, or a sail area exceeding 15 m2 for sailing boats.
~A power output greater than 15 kW, or a sail area exceeding 30 m2.
~A power output greater than 50 kW, or a sail area exceeding 10 m2.
####[html]ONI art. 134, al. 5 applies to boats of more than 30 kW and to sailing boats whose sail area exceeds 15 m2.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 134 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart134-df53e657-4b7336b2:: [html]Which of these devices are INDIVIDUAL lifesaving appliances within the meaning of the ONI? {
~%50%Lifejackets with collars
~%50%Lifebuoys
~%-100%Boarding life rafts
####[html]ONI art. 134\: lifejackets with collars and lifebuoys \= individual; boarding life rafts are collective.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 134 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart134-df53e657-7afccc1f:: [html]What minimum buoyancy must an individual lifesaving device have (general case)? {
=At least 75 N
~At least 750 N
~At least 50 N
####[html]ONI art. 134, al. 2\: at least 75 N (except for vessels referred to in art. 134a).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 134 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart143a-26df4c56-438fe381:: [html]For a loaded cargo boat ready to depart to be considered as having sufficient stability, what conditions does the text require? {
=The heeling angle does not exceed 5 degrees and the side of the deck, at its lowest point, does not dip into the water.
~The heeling angle does not exceed 15 degrees and the deck may dip up to 5 cm.
~The heeling angle does not exceed 10 degrees, regardless of the position of the deck.
####[html]According to ONI art. 143a, al. 2, the heeling angle must not exceed 5 degrees and the lowest side of the deck must not dip into the water.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 143a — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart143a-26df4c56-f70cd9b2:: [html]What does ONI art. 143a provide regarding the metacentric height of the loaded boat ready to depart? {
=It must not be less than 1 m.
~It must not be less than 0.5 m.
~It must not exceed 1 m.
####[html]ONI art. 143a, al. 2 specifies that the metacentric height of the loaded boat ready to depart must not be less than 1 m.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 143a — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart144-82fa0c6a-4d75de58:: [html]According to ONI art. 144, what is the prescribed freeboard for floating equipment? {
=90 cm in zone 2 and 45 cm in zone 3.
~30 cm in zone 2 and 15 cm in zone 3.
~100 cm in zone 2 and 50 cm in zone 3.
####[html]ONI art. 144, al. 5 sets the freeboard of floating equipment at 90 cm in zone 2 and 45 cm in zone 3.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 144 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart144-82fa0c6a-d0e87234:: [html]According to ONI art. 144, what is the freeboard of an undecked cargo boat in zone 2? {
=100 cm.
~50 cm.
~30 cm.
####[html]ONI art. 144, al. 2, let. b sets the freeboard of undecked boats at 100 cm in zone 2.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 144 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart146-e6f12005-ab00c057:: [html]Which of these statements about the collision bulkhead is FALSE according to ONI art. 146? {
=It may include doors and hatches if they are watertight.
~It must be watertight and built from one side of the hull to the other.
~It must be built from the bottom of the hold up to the deck.
####[html]ONI art. 146, al. 5 prohibits any door, hatch or opening in the collision bulkhead.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 146 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart146-e6f12005-e946225b:: [html]According to ONI art. 146, with how many bulkheads must a cargo boat at least be fitted? {
=At least one collision bulkhead and two bulkheads for the engine room.
~At least three collision bulkheads at the bow.
~At least one bulkhead for the engine room only.
####[html]ONI art. 146, al. 2 requires at least one collision bulkhead and two bulkheads for the engine room.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 146 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart148g-5963b92c-9c9d48f2:: [html]Regarding the «CE» marking on sport boats placed on the market, what does ONI art. 148g say? {
=The obligation to affix the «CE» marking is not applicable, but if it has already been affixed in accordance with the EU provisions, it may remain affixed.
~The «CE» marking is mandatory for all sport boats placed on the market.
~The «CE» marking must be removed if it was affixed in accordance with the EU provisions.
####[html]ONI art. 148g, al. 2 provides that the «CE» marking is not mandatory but may remain affixed if it has already been affixed in accordance with the EU provisions.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 148g — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart148g-5963b92c-fb63b421:: [html]In which language must the documentation relating to a sport boat be presented to the competent authority according to ONI art. 148g? {
=In an official language of Switzerland or in English.
~Exclusively in German.
~Only in the manufacturer's language.
####[html]ONI art. 148g, al. 6 requires that the documentation be presented in an official language of Switzerland or in English.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 148g — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart150-092b6842-4b540149:: [html]ONI art. 150 allows the crew to be reduced by one deckhand, on boats of less than 350 tonnes and in good visibility. Which of these conditions is required? {
=The travel time between the points of departure and arrival does not exceed 45 minutes.
~The travel time between the points of departure and arrival does not exceed 90 minutes.
~The boat must transport exclusively dangerous goods.
####[html]ONI art. 150, al. 4, let. b sets a maximum of 45 minutes of travel time allowing this reduction.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 150 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart150-092b6842-f132f133:: [html]According to ONI art. 150, what is as a general rule the crew complement of a motorized cargo boat with a loading capacity greater than 1000 t? {
=2 deckhands.
~1 deckhand.
~3 deckhands.
####[html]ONI art. 150, al. 2, let. a provides for 2 deckhands for motorized boats of more than 1000 t loading capacity.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 150 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart163-1f9efaa2-2cbbddc1:: [html]According to ONI art. 163, in which case is a construction number not necessary? {
=For boats that are not built by professionals.
~For all pleasure boats, without exception.
~For priority passenger boats.
####[html]ONI art. 163, al. 1, let. g provides that a construction number is not necessary for boats not built by professionals.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 163 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart163-1f9efaa2-82d4fd8b:: [html]According to ONI art. 163, the granting of other derogations (not listed) requires in principle\: {
=The consent of the OFT.
~The agreement of the Federal Council.
~No additional authorization.
####[html]ONI art. 163, al. 3 provides that other derogations may only be granted with the consent of the OFT.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 163 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart96a-83a6b5e5-7f8734f7:: [html]According to ONI art. 96a, in which case may a collective navigation permit be used? {
=For breakdown-assistance and towing trips.
~For regular commercial passenger transport.
~For any private leisure trip of the owner.
####[html]ONI art. 96a, al. 3, let. a authorizes the use of the collective permit for breakdown-assistance and towing trips.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 96a — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniart96a-83a6b5e5-d9307017:: [html]What minimum third-party liability insurance coverage is required for the issuance of a collective navigation permit according to ONI art. 96a? {
=Two million francs per accident.
~One million francs per accident.
~Five million francs per accident.
####[html]ONI art. 96a, al. 1, let. c requires a minimum coverage of two million francs per accident.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI art. 96a — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Signs

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig1-466f4128-adba28ab:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this light signal mean? {
=Steady light visible from all sides
~Quick-flashing light
~Blue quick-flashing light
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 1 — "Steady light visible from all sides".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 1 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig10-ff141136-141ef391:: [html]At night, which lights must a sailing vessel under motor (sails hoisted or not) carry? {
=A white masthead light, green and red side lights, and a white stern light
~Only an ordinary white light visible from all sides
~A white masthead light and a tricolour light combining the side lights and the stern light at the top of the mast
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 10 — white masthead light, green/red side lights, white stern light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 10 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig11-a7ce07dd-21adc0a7:: [html]A sailing vessel under motor may combine its side lights and its stern light into a single tricolour light. Where is this tricolour light placed, and which other light is still required? {
=A white masthead light, with the tricolour light placed at the top of the mast or near it
~A white masthead light, with the tricolour light placed on the stern at water level
~No masthead light, and a white stern light separate from the tricolour light
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 11 — white masthead light; side lights and stern light combined into a tricolour light at the top of the mast or near it.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 11 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig14-45636e4f-a9566c54:: [html]At night, which light must a non-motorised vessel sailing alone or in a towed convoy carry? {
=An ordinary white light visible from all sides
~A white masthead light with green and red side lights
~An ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 14 — non-motorised vessels, alone or towed\: ordinary white light visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 14 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig15-42ccc9b1-58121b9e:: [html]At night, which light must a vessel under sail (without motor) carry as a minimum? {
=An ordinary white light visible from all sides
~Green and red side lights and a white stern light
~A white masthead light and a tricolour light at the top of the mast
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 15 — vessels under sail\: ordinary white light visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 15 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig17-77b94b84-f9419446:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this light signal mean? {
~Flashing light
~Fixed light visible from all sides
=Tricolour light placed at the top of the mast or near it
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 17 — « Tricolour light placed at the top of the mast or near it ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 17 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig18-ec6e52d1-be5f1ec2:: [html]At night, a vessel carries two superimposed lights visible from all sides, a stern light and a bicolour light (or separate side lights). What are the colours of the two superimposed lights? {
=The upper light red, the lower light green
~The upper light green, the lower light red
~Both lights white
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 18 — two superimposed lights visible from all sides\: the upper red, the lower green.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 18 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig2-a59b06e5-dd939f47:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this light signal mean? {
~Blue quick-flashing light
~Steady light visible from all sides
=Quick-flashing light
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 2 — "Quick-flashing light".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 2 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig20-188a22fa-0b55ae68:: [html]At night, when the safety of navigation requires it, how must floating equipment be marked? {
=By lighting that allows its outline to be made out
~By an ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
~By a white masthead light and green and red side lights
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 20 — floating equipment\: when safety requires it, lighting that allows the outline to be made out.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 20 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig21-a4c59f38-c34d0dd7:: [html]In addition to the usual navigation lights, which distinctive light must a priority vessel carry at night? {
=A bright green light visible from all sides, placed at least 1 m higher than the masthead light
~A bright red light visible from all sides, placed at least 1 m higher than the masthead light
~An ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 21 — priority vessels\: a bright green light visible from all sides, at least 1 m above the masthead light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 21 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig22-f87cb685-5b821c7e:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~No mooring
=Green ball
~The clearance height of the passage is limited
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 22 — "Green ball".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 22 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig23-78f17195-0511eff5:: [html]To indicate that it must be protected against wash, which additional lights does a vessel carry at night, in addition to the prescribed lights? {
=An ordinary red light visible from all sides above an ordinary white light visible from all sides
~An ordinary white light above an ordinary red light, both visible from all sides
~Two superimposed ordinary red lights visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 23 — protection against wash\: red light visible from all sides above a white light visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 23 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig24-7c82046a-751565a1:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
=A flag whose upper half is red and lower half white
~Swinging a red flag
~Two superimposed white flags
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 24 — « A flag whose upper half is red and lower half white ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 24 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig25-727c3760-7b5e66e7:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
=Two flags, the upper red and the lower white
~Two superimposed white flags
~Swinging a red flag
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 25 — « Two flags, the upper red and the lower white ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 25 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig27-6270f90c-7407e9b2:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Mandatory stop under certain conditions
=Two white flags one above the other
~Anchoring permitted
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 27 — "Two white flags one above the other".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 27 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig29-98cd55c4-d726e2d2:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Yellow ball
~Police boats and boats of other services
=Yellow buoys marking each anchor
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 29 — "Yellow buoys marking each anchor".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 29 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig3-72140816-b4054b28:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~No turning
~Passage permitted
=Ball
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 3 — "Ball".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 3 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig30-b7c4f864-bba9d2a3:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Yellow buoys marking each anchor
~No anchoring
=Police boats and boats of other services
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 30 — "Police boats and boats of other services".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 30 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig31-056d2c35-7e11146e:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this light signal mean? {
~Quick-flashing light
=Blue quick-flashing light
~Steady light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 31 — "Blue quick-flashing light".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 31 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig32-8474c209-eff47504:: [html]Which signal does a vessel of the police, the border guard or the fisheries inspectorate hoist when it wants to make contact with another vessel? {
=The letter «K» flag, whose half on the staff side is yellow and the other half blue
~The letter «K» flag, whose upper half is red and the other half white
~An entirely red flag
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 32 — letter «K» flag, half on the staff side yellow, the other half blue.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 32 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig33-f3928ea5-f49826f9:: [html]At night, which light must a professional fishing vessel carry? {
=An ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
~An ordinary white light visible from all sides
~An ordinary red light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 33 — professional fishing vessels\: ordinary yellow light visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 33 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig34-38f8c8ba-1e95dac4:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Pass only in the direction indicated
=Yellow ball
~Mandatory stop under certain conditions
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 34 — "Yellow ball".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 34 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig35-49c140b6-ea42b41e:: [html]Which daytime signal must a vessel trolling for fish display? {
=A white ball
~A green ball visible from all sides
~An ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 35 — vessels trolling for fish\: white ball.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 35 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig36-f348b5a7-5f382b2c:: [html]In the case of underwater diving carried out from the shore, which signal must be displayed? {
=The letter «A» board (a swallow-tailed pennant, half on the staff side white, the other half blue)
~The letter «K» flag (half on the staff side yellow, the other half blue)
~A white ball visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 36 — diving from the shore\: letter «A» board, white/blue swallow-tailed pennant.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 36 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig37-6c099ecd-aca1d666:: [html]In the case of underwater diving carried out from a body of water, how must the letter «A» board be displayed? {
=The letter «A» board (white/blue pennant) visible from all sides
~The letter «A» board facing only towards the shore
~A red flag visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 37 — diving from a body of water\: letter «A» board (white/blue pennant) visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 37 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig39-a1ae0684-e241f96a:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
=Waving a red flag
~The width of the passage is limited
~Pass only in the direction indicated
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 39 — "Waving a red flag".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 39 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig4-6f7c0dce-b7d748f5:: [html]At night, which lights must a motorised vessel sailing alone (or a tug) carry? {
=A bright white masthead (or bow) light, bright green and bright red side lights, and an ordinary white stern light
~Only an ordinary white light visible from all sides
~A bright white light and a bright green light visible from all sides placed higher than the masthead light
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 4 — motorised vessels alone/tugs\: bright white masthead light, bright green/red side lights, ordinary white stern light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 4 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig40-dc3b2f2d-1f3cdb85:: [html]At night, how does a vessel in distress signal its situation? {
=By swinging a light in a circular motion
~By swinging a light (without a circular motion)
~By showing two fixed superimposed red lights
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 40 — vessels in distress\: swing a light in a circular motion.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 40 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig41-043d783d-a74bc641:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
~Swinging a red flag
=Swinging a red flag, or any other suitable object, in a circular motion
~Two superimposed white flags
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 41 — « Swinging a red flag, or any other suitable object, in a circular motion ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 41 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig42-f759937d-93e52f7c:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
=A slow, repeated up-and-down movement of the arms extended to each side
~Permission to moor
~B. in the indicated direction only
####[html]ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 42 — « A slow, repeated up-and-down movement of the arms extended to each side ».<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 42 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig43-f7b06d9e-dbc23978:: [html]At night, how does a piece of floating equipment (or a vessel at work, aground or sunk) indicate the sides on which passage is clear? {
=By an ordinary red light and an ordinary white light
~By an ordinary red light alone
~By an ordinary green light and an ordinary white light
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 43 — side where passage is clear\: ordinary red light + ordinary white light; side not clear\: ordinary red light alone.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 43 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig44-1e963c8a-c5194529:: [html]By day, which flag indicates the side on which passage is NOT clear near a piece of floating equipment or a vessel at work? {
=A red flag
~A flag whose upper half is red and lower half white
~An entirely white flag
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 44 — side where passage is not clear\: red flag; side clear\: red/white flag.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 44 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig45-46d6d361-a22d76a7:: [html]By day, which signal indicates the side on which passage is clear near a piece of floating equipment or a vessel at work (two-flag variant)? {
=Two superimposed flags, the upper red and the lower white
~Two superimposed flags, the upper white and the lower red
~A single red flag
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 45 — side clear\: two superimposed flags, upper red, lower white; side not clear\: red flag.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 45 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig5-b9cc2457-cb3b6339:: [html]At night, where is the masthead light (bright white light) of a pushed convoy placed? {
=On the leading vessel
~On the pushing vessel, at the rear of the convoy
~At the centre of the convoy, on the most visible vessel
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 5 — pushed convoys\: bright white masthead light placed on the leading vessel.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 5 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig8-abe2e33a-a6b4ecda:: [html]At night, which lights may a professional fishing, sport or motorised pleasure vessel (or a sailing vessel under motor) carry under this simplified variant? {
=A white light visible from all sides and green and red side lights
~A white masthead light, green/red side lights and a separate white stern light
~Only an ordinary white light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 8 — white light visible from all sides + green and red side lights.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 8 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe2fig9-ea35d966-f397d177:: [html]Under this variant, how may the side lights of a motorised sport/pleasure vessel (or sailing vessel under motor) carrying a white light visible from all sides be arranged in the forward area? {
=Side by side in the forward area, or as a bicolour light
~Combined with the stern light into a tricolour light at the top of the mast
~Replaced by a single ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]ONI Annexe 2, fig. 9 — white light visible from all sides + green/red side lights, placed side by side in the forward area or as a bicolour light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 2 – fig. 9 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe3fig1-74a2f981-0fa9d939:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this sound signal mean? {
~Two lights one above the other
=Peals of a bell
~Yellow buoys marking each anchor
####[html]ONI Annexe 3 – fig. 1 — "Peals of a bell".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 3 – fig. 1 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig1-9fc6fa6d-75530350:: [html]What does the general prohibition signal (circular board with a red border and a red bar) placed on a body of water mean? {
=No passage
~The channel is limited to a certain distance from the shore
~Recommended passage for crossing under a bridge
