}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig52-979bca5a-634a8152:: [html]To mark a shoal near the shore, which marks are used on the open-water side and on the shore side? {
=Open-water side\: cylinders; shore side\: cones
~Open-water side\: cones; shore side\: cylinders
~Open-water side and shore side\: yellow floats
####[html]ONI Annexe 4, fig. 52 — shoal near the shore\: open-water side cylinders, shore side cones.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 52 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig53-12f3a908-03473a84:: [html]For a marked channel in a shoal area, how are the right and left sides marked as seen from the open water? {
=Right side\: green cones; left side\: red cylinders
~Right side\: red cylinders; left side\: green cones
~Both sides\: cones point down painted red
####[html]ONI Annexe 4, fig. 53 — channel in a shoal area\: right side (seen from open water) green cones, left side red cylinders.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 53 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig54-c3024fd8-c40d2b61:: [html]How does a cardinal mark indicate the North quadrant of an extended obstacle? {
=Two cones one above the other, both points up
~Two cones one above the other, both points down
~Two cones one above the other, the lower cone point down and the upper cone point up
####[html]ONI Annexe 4, fig. 54 — North quadrant\: two cones one above the other, both points up.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 54 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig55-ab288aa3-0a6785f6:: [html]Cardinal marks indicate an extended shoal by indicating the North and West quadrants. What do they indicate? {
=That the deep water lies in the North and West quadrants
~That the obstacle lies in the North and West quadrants
~That passage is prohibited in the North and West quadrants
####[html]ONI Annexe 4, fig. 55 — the marks indicate that the deep water lies in the North and West quadrants.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 55 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig6-3fd0dd21-2280f456:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this board mean? {
~No passage for motorized boats
~End of a prohibition or an obligation
=No windsurfing
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 6 — "No windsurfing".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 6 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig63-d93729c2-4772e7a1:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this sound signal mean? {
=Continuous peals of a bell
~Mandatory stop under certain conditions
~No anchoring
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 63 — "Continuous peals of a bell".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 63 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig64-cf3ef722-1e69aa0a:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Swimming prohibited
=Wailing of a siren
~Pass only in the direction indicated
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 64 — "Wailing of a siren".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 64 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig7-b49d058f-7f440462:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this board mean? {
~No turning
=No overtaking
~No meeting or overtaking
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 7 — "No overtaking".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 7 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig8-84092d86-6d075eb9:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this board mean? {
~No passage for sailing boats
~Water-skiing prohibited
=No meeting or overtaking
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 8 — "No meeting or overtaking".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 8 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-oni-oniannexe4fig9-c530e67e-6281e520:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this board mean? {
~No turning
=No berthing
~End of a prohibition or an obligation
####[html]ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 9 — "No berthing".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1979/337_337_337/fr">ONI Annexe 4 – fig. 9 — Ordonnance sur la navigation intérieure (ONI), RS 747.201.1 (2022-01-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig10-14b9e7fd-b4d92347:: [html]At night, which lights must a sailing vessel under motor (sails hoisted or not) carry? {
=A white masthead light, green and red side lights, and a white stern light
~A white light visible from all sides and green and red side lights, without a masthead light
~Only an ordinary white light visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 10 — white masthead light, green and red side lights, white stern light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 10 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig11-a62f797a-28e056bf:: [html]A sailing vessel under motor may, instead of separate side lights and a stern light, combine these lights. How and where is this combined light arranged, in addition to the white masthead light? {
=A tricolour light combining the side lights and the stern light, placed at the top of the mast or near it
~A bicolour light placed in the forward area, with the stern light remaining separate
~A white light visible from all sides placed at the stern
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 11 — white masthead light and tricolour light (sides + stern) at the top of the mast or near it.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 11 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig14-3c63d9dd-44fa7b4c:: [html]At night, which lights must a vessel or floating equipment being towed carry? {
=An ordinary white masthead light and an ordinary white stern light
~A white masthead light, green and red side lights, and a white stern light
~A single ordinary white light visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 14 — ordinary white masthead light and ordinary white stern light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 14 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig16-876eb8a5-b940dbfa:: [html]At night, how does a non-motorised vessel navigating alone or in a towed convoy mark itself? {
=By an ordinary white light visible from all sides
~By a white masthead light and green and red side lights
~By an ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 16 — ordinary white light visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 16 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig17-98ce7451-6d59eca5:: [html]At night, by which light may a vessel under sail (without motor) mark itself in the simplest way? {
=An ordinary white light visible from all sides
~A white masthead light accompanied by green and red side lights
~A tricolour light placed at the top of the mast
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 17 — ordinary white light visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 17 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig18-71d213c1-ec131935:: [html]At night, a vessel under sail carrying side lights and a stern light\: what are these lights? {
=Green and red side lights and a white stern light
~Green and red side lights, a white stern light and a white masthead light
~An ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 18 — green and red side lights, white stern light (no masthead light).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 18 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig19-5a1f0630-85b8d238:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this light signal mean? {
=Tricolour light placed at the top of the mast or near it
~Either a red flag and a white flag
~Vessels navigating alone or tugs
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 19 — "Tricolour light placed at the top of the mast or near it".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 19 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig20-478da848-6f852221:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
=Additional night marking of priority passenger vessels under way
~Pushed convoys
~Vessels navigating alone or tugs
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 20 — "Additional night marking of priority passenger vessels under way".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 20 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig21-b53b2ab6-f4e1817b:: [html]At night, how does a vessel that has become unable to manoeuvre signal its situation, in addition to its ordinary lights? {
=By swinging a red light and/or by sounding the prescribed sound signal
~By swinging a white light visible from all sides
~By showing a green ball visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 21 — a red light swung and/or the prescribed sound signal.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 21 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig22-a4ed91e3-91f3e1b1:: [html]At night, how may a vessel unable to manoeuvre mark itself by means of fixed lights visible from all sides? {
=Two red lights one above the other, about 1 m apart, visible from all sides
~Two white lights one above the other about 1 m apart
~A red light above a white light, both visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 22 — two red lights one above the other about 1 m apart, visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 22 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig24-b5accf5f-3ac2b83e:: [html]At night, how must floating equipment at a standstill be marked? {
=Lit in such a way that its contours are recognisable
~By an ordinary red light above an ordinary white light
~By a black ball visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 24 — floating equipment at a standstill lit so that its contours are recognisable.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 24 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig25-3522004d-7b6c6353:: [html]At night, a vessel carrying out works or sounding operations\: what does it show on the side where passage is free, and on the side where it is not free? {
=Free side\: ordinary red light above an ordinary white light; non-free side\: ordinary red light
~Free side\: ordinary white light alone; non-free side\: ordinary white light above a red light
~Free side\: green light; non-free side\: red light
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 25 — free side\: ordinary red light and ordinary white light; non-free side\: ordinary red light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 25 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig26-dc7b5242-1c811124:: [html]At night, how are a vessel's anchors marked on the water? {
=By buoys carrying an ordinary white light
~By buoys carrying an ordinary red light
~By black balls visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 26 — anchors marked by buoys carrying an ordinary white light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 26 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig27-7ff66719-e10f841a:: [html]By day, by which signal does a priority passenger vessel indicate its priority? {
=A green ball, visible from all sides
~A yellow ball, visible from all sides
~A white ball, visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 27 — green ball visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 27 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig28-d7ffe00b-99d86313:: [html]By day, how does a vessel unable to manoeuvre signal its situation by means of a flag? {
=By swinging a red flag and/or by sounding the prescribed sound signal
~By swinging a white flag visible from all sides
~By hoisting a green ball visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 28 — a red flag swung and/or the prescribed sound signal.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 28 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig29-c89b6222-e0552ef7:: [html]By day, how may a vessel unable to manoeuvre mark itself by means of fixed marks visible from all sides? {
=Two black balls one above the other, about 1 m apart, visible from all sides
~Two green balls one above the other visible from all sides
~A white ball visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 29 — two black balls one above the other about 1 m apart, visible from all sides.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 29 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig30-0b7fee06-e3a167e6:: [html]By day, a vessel carrying out works\: what does it show on the side where passage is free, and on the side where it is not free? {
=Free side\: a red and white flag (or a red flag and a white flag); non-free side\: a red flag
~Free side\: a red flag; non-free side\: a red and white flag
~Free side\: a green ball; non-free side\: a black ball
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 30 — free side\: red and white flag; non-free side\: red flag.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 30 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig32-79bb39ae-96d4982f:: [html]At night, how does a vessel or floating establishment to be protected against wash mark itself? {
=By an ordinary red light above an ordinary white light
~By an ordinary white light above an ordinary red light
~By two red lights one above the other visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 32 — at night\: ordinary red light above an ordinary white light.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 32 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig34-1152b879-08abbf2d:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64," alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
=Either a red flag and a white flag
~No passage outside the area indicated
~Boats navigating alone or tugboats
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 34 — "Either a red flag and a white flag".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 34 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig35-d034546c-cad103a3:: [html]What special light do the vessels of the control authorities, fire services and rescue services carry when on a mission? {
=A scintillating blue light
~A bright green light visible from all sides
~A scintillating yellow light
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 35 — scintillating blue light for vessels on a mission.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 35 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig37-adfe31a5-ac6b4a42:: [html]What flag does a vessel of the control authorities hoist when it wishes to enter into communication with another vessel? {
=The letter "K" flag
~The letter "A" board
~A red flag
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 37 — letter "K" flag to enter into communication.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 37 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig38-a273c571-c54f62c3:: [html]How does a vessel in distress call for help, both at night and by day? {
=At night\: a red light swung in a circle; by day\: a red flag or other object swung in a circle
~At night\: a white light swung; by day\: a green ball hoisted
~At night\: two red lights one above the other; by day\: two black balls one above the other
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 38 — distress\: red light (night) or red flag/object (day) swung in a circle.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 38 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig4-4bacf613-79a3ca91:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Pushed convoys
=Boats navigating alone or tugboats
~Pleasure boats
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 4 — "Boats navigating alone or tugboats".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 4 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig40-0560d461-ab316f10:: [html]What signal indicates underwater diving carried out from the shore? {
=A board bearing the letter "A"
~A flag bearing the letter "K"
~A yellow ball visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 40 — letter "A" board for diving from the shore.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 40 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig41-7dd1f930-01e5a379:: [html]What signal does a vessel used for underwater diving carry when the diving is done from a body of water? {
=A board bearing the letter "A"
~A white ball visible from all sides
~A flag bearing the letter "K"
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 41 — letter "A" board for diving from a body of water.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 41 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig42-12aa6344-90872a93:: [html]What signal does a vessel trolling and towing one or more floats or spreaders carry? {
=A white ball, visible from all sides
~A yellow ball, visible from all sides
~A green ball, visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 42 — white ball visible from all sides for trolling.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 42 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig43-9140f412-1168f6ad:: [html]What signal does a professional fishing vessel in operation carry? {
=A yellow ball, visible from all sides
~A white ball, visible from all sides
~A green ball, visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 43 — yellow ball visible from all sides for professional fishing in operation.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 43 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig5-466235f4-f2f518b6:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Pleasure boats
~Boats navigating alone or tugboats
=Pushed convoys
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 5 — "Pushed convoys".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 5 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig6-62565189-ad1c8a52:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this sign mean? {
~Pushed convoys
=Pleasure boats
~Boats navigating alone or tugboats
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 6 — "Pleasure boats".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 6 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig7-90f4e02f-3f76a909:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=" alt\="">What does this signal mean? {
~Pushed convoys
~Vessels navigating alone or tugs
=Professional fishing vessels, motorised pleasure craft
####[html]RNL Annexe I – fig. 7 — "Professional fishing vessels, motorised pleasure craft".<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 7 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeifig8-928d2012-7b3112b7:: [html]At night, which lights may a motorised pleasure craft (or a sailing vessel under motor) carry under this simplified configuration? {
=A white light visible from all sides and green and red side lights
~A white masthead light, green and red side lights and a separate white stern light
~An ordinary yellow light visible from all sides
####[html]RNL Annexe I, fig. 8 — white light visible from all sides and green and red side lights.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL Annexe I – fig. 8 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlannexeiiifig1-81fc5ae2-c254c3d6:: [html]<img src\="data\:image/png;base64,\=\=" alt\="">What does this board mean? {
~No anchoring
=No passage
