$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Seamanship

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœuddechaiseintér-434f37a7:: [html]What does the text confirm about the bowline when it is not under tension? {
=It is easy to undo, even when wet and after having been subjected to a very strong pull or to tightening caused by drying out.
~It becomes impossible to undo as soon as it gets wet.
~It can only be adjusted by applying strong tension to the standing part.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Intérêts, when not under tension it is easy to undo even when wet and after a strong pull.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_de_chaise">Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Intérêts — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (236353098)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœuddechaiseintér-83239d56:: [html]According to the text, how does the bowline react when tension increases? {
=The stronger the tension, the more it locks, while still untying just as easily.
~The stronger the tension, the more it tends to slip and come undone.
~Tension has no effect on its locking, which depends on an intermediate mechanical system.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Intérêts, the stronger the tension, the more the knot locks and the more easily it unties.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_de_chaise">Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Intérêts — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (236353098)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœuddechaiseprése-6e8aa766:: [html]According to the text, the bowline is also called\: {
=Bowline knot (nœud de bouline).
~Clove hitch.
~Hangman's knot.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Présentation, the bowline is also called the nœud de bouline.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_de_chaise">Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Présentation — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (236353098)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœuddechaiseroide-3f4a81a1:: [html]Why is the bowline described as the king of knots, according to the text? {
=It is a reliable loop knot that does not slip under tension and unties easily even after strong tension.
~It is the only knot that is impossible to untie once tightened.
~It can only be made with a specialized tool and with two hands.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Roi des nœuds, its quality as a reliable loop knot that does not slip and unties easily justifies it.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_de_chaise">Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Roi des nœuds — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (236353098)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœuddechaiseroide-7f29e223:: [html]Why is the bowline described as the “king of knots”? {
=It is a reliable loop knot that does not slip under tension and unties easily
~It tightens more and more under tension until it becomes impossible to untie
~It is used only to join two ropes of the same diameter
####[html]The bowline is a reliable loop that does not slip and unties easily.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_de_chaise">Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Roi des nœuds — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (236353098)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœuddechaiseroide-f42e5f81:: [html]Regarding the methods for making the bowline, which statement(s) does the text confirm? {
~%50%There are several methods for making it, up to 18 including the variants.
~%50%Only two classic methods are recognized for teaching, knitted or prepared.
~%-100%A single unique method of making it is accepted throughout the world.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Roi des nœuds, there are up to 18 methods including variants but two classic teaching methods.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_de_chaise">Matelotage — Nœud de chaise \: Roi des nœuds — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (236353098)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœudlienganses-27-28ba601c:: [html]According to the text, what does the hangman's knot illustrate regarding bight knots? {
=It can be easily undone if the loop is free, but tightens around the restraint under the weight of the hanged person.
~It can never be undone, whether the loop is free or restrained.
~It loosens automatically as soon as weight is applied to the loop.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Ganses, the hangman's knot comes undone if the loop is free but tightens under the weight of the hanged person.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_(lien)">Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Ganses — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (235796348)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœudlienganses-27-c0d99855:: [html]According to the text, what is a bight (ganse)? {
=A curved portion of rope, with no crossing or overlapping.
~A tight crossing of two rope ends.
~A rope braided from three metal strands.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Ganses, a bight is a curved portion of rope with no crossing or overlapping.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_(lien)">Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Ganses — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (235796348)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœudlienpropriété-8de17e1b:: [html]According to the text, what is the strength of a rope fitted with a bowline compared to a clove hitch? {
=The bowline retains an exceptional strength of 89%, whereas the clove hitch halves it.
~The clove hitch retains 89% of the strength, against half for the bowline.
~Both knots reduce the rope's strength by exactly half.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Propriétés, the clove hitch reduces strength by half whereas the bowline reaches 89%.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_(lien)">Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Propriétés — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (235796348)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœudlienpropriété-af89cb8d:: [html]According to the text, which criterion makes it possible to evaluate and choose the most suitable knot? {
=The strength of the knot, in particular whether or not it weakens the rope in case of violent jerks.
~The color of the rope used to make it.
~The purchase price of the cord.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Propriétés, the strength of the knot is paramount, especially in case of violent jerks.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_(lien)">Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Propriétés — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (235796348)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœudlienprésentat-27c16d5a:: [html]According to the text, which statement about the use of knots is correct? {
=The art of knots mainly developed in sailing vessels and then in sport or leisure boating.
~Knots have never been used outside the maritime domain.
~Knowledge of knots has become completely useless since the appearance of specialized equipment.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Présentation, knots developed in sailing vessels and then in boating.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_(lien)">Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Présentation — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (235796348)</a>
}

::q-matelotagewp-matelotagenœudlienprésentat-802b92e8:: [html]According to the text, what is a knot? {
=The intertwining or interlacing of one or more ropes or other flexible, thread-like objects.
~Exclusively the interlacing of two rigid metal cables.
~An assembly of planks intended to reinforce a hull.
####[html]According to Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Présentation, a knot is the intertwining or interlacing of flexible, thread-like objects.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nœud_(lien)">Matelotage — Nœud (lien) \: Présentation — Wikipédia — nœuds marins (matelotage) (235796348)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Border waters

::q-rnl-rnlart16-b7510c8f-75a2bba2:: [html]According to RNL art. 16, which statement is correct concerning events on the water? {
=When authorising an event, the authority may permit derogations from certain provisions of the Regulation provided that the safety of navigation is not affected
~Nautical events never require prior authorisation
~In the case of a binational event, a single authority decides without informing the other
####[html]RNL art. 16, para. 3, allows derogations from certain provisions provided that the safety of navigation is not affected.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 16 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart16-b7510c8f-d1f31b5c:: [html]Under which condition in particular is authorisation for a nautical event granted according to RNL art. 16? {
=If the prescribed civil liability insurance has been taken out
~If the event takes place exclusively in Swiss waters
~If all participants hold a category A permit
####[html]RNL art. 16, para. 2, let. b, requires that the prescribed civil liability insurance has been taken out.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 16 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart62-ff70e033-8bbd322b:: [html]When two vessels follow directly opposite courses with a risk of collision, how must they manoeuvre? {
=Each turns to starboard so as to pass port to port
~Each turns to port so as to pass starboard to starboard
~Both maintain their course and speed without any manoeuvre
####[html]RNL art. 62, let. c, provides that each vessel turns to starboard so as to pass port to port.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 62 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart62-ff70e033-8cc77ef7:: [html]When two vessels follow crossing courses with a possible danger of collision, which one must give way? {
=The vessel that sees the other on its starboard side
~The vessel that sees the other on its port side
~The faster of the two vessels
####[html]According to RNL art. 62, let. b, the vessel that sees the other on its starboard side must give way.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 62 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart64-284d0c2c-a9e2a5f1:: [html]According to RNL art. 64, which statement is FALSE concerning sailboards and kitesurfs? {
=Other vessels must give way to sailboards and kitesurfs
~Sailboards and kitesurfs give way to all other vessels
~Every vessel must give way to a vessel unable to manoeuvre that signals its presence
####[html]RNL art. 64, para. 2, let. f, states on the contrary that sailboards and kitesurfs give way to all other vessels.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 64 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart64-284d0c2c-b1177e2f:: [html]Faced with a vessel unable to manoeuvre that signals its presence, what must every other vessel do? {
=Keep clear of that vessel
~Maintain its course and speed
~Overtake it on the starboard side
####[html]RNL art. 64, para. 1\: every vessel must keep clear of a vessel unable to manoeuvre that signals its presence.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 64 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart64-284d0c2c-bf5c412c:: [html]According to the right-of-way rules, which vessel(s) must a sailing vessel give way to? {
~%50%Passenger vessels having right of way and towed convoys
~%50%Cargo vessels
~%-100%Rowing boats
####[html]According to RNL art. 64, para. 2, the sailing vessel gives way in particular to passenger vessels having right of way, towed convoys and cargo vessels, but not to rowing boats.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 64 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart64-284d0c2c-ecad6807:: [html]When meeting, which vessels must every vessel — apart from priority passenger vessels and towed convoys — keep clear of? {
=Cargo vessels
~Pleasure craft
~Sailing sport boats
####[html]RNL art. 64, para. 2 let. b\: it keeps clear of cargo vessels.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 64 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart84-4e300df7-385c5f4f:: [html]According to RNL art. 84, under what conditions are the boarding and disembarking of passengers authorised? {
=Only at facilities permitted by the competent authority and after the operator has ensured that the vessel is properly moored
~At any point on the shore as soon as the vessel slows down
~Without mooring if the safety of the passengers appears to be guaranteed
####[html]RNL art. 84, para. 1, authorises boarding and disembarking only at permitted facilities and after verification of the mooring and of safety.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 84 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart84-4e300df7-67a725ae:: [html]Concerning the order of use of landing stages, which statement is FALSE according to RNL art. 84? {
=Boarding passengers may access the landing stage at the same time as passengers are disembarking
~A passenger may not board or disembark without the formal authorisation of the operator or their agent
~The waiting rule does not apply to landing stages equipped with independent entrances and exits
####[html]RNL art. 84, para. 4, requires on the contrary that boarding passengers access the landing stage only after the disembarking passengers have left it, except where there are independent entrances/exits.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 84 — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart86a-00f78534-0861debe:: [html]Which radio channel is designated as the alert channel (Lake Distress) in the equipment of passenger vessels? {
=Channel 16
~Channel 12
~Channel K
####[html]RNL art. 86a, para. 1, let. c, designates channel 16 as the alert channel (Lake Distress), channel 12 being operational and channel K being the command coordination channel.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 86a — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart86a-00f78534-eb018a29:: [html]Among the communication and information equipment, which items apply only to passenger vessels making an international trip? {
~%50%The radar device
~%50%The rate-of-turn indicator
~%-100%The radio installation capable of transmitting on alert channel 16
####[html]According to RNL art. 86a, para. 2, only the requirements of para. 1, let. a (radar) and b (rate-of-turn indicator) apply solely to international trips.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 86a — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart86f-185c6500-0c8038aa:: [html]What minimum buoyancy in fresh water must the collective lifesaving devices of a passenger vessel provide per person? {
=At least 750 N per person
~At least 500 N per person
~At least 100 N per person
####[html]According to RNL art. 86f, para. 2, let. b, the buoyancy in fresh water must be at least 750 N per person.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 86f — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

::q-rnl-rnlart86f-185c6500-d26c4b04:: [html]Concerning the inflatable collective lifesaving devices on board passenger vessels, which statements are correct? {
~%50%They must consist of at least two separate air compartments
~%50%They must maintain a stable trim even if only half of the air compartments are inflated
~%-100%They must inflate only by manual command, never automatically
####[html]RNL art. 86f, para. 3, requires at least two separate compartments and a stable trim even with half of the compartments inflated, the inflation being able to be automatic or manual.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.fedlex.admin.ch/eli/cc/1978/1994_1993_1993/fr">RNL art. 86f — Règlement de la navigation sur le Léman (RNL), RS 747.221.1 (2019-06-01)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Sailing

::q-voilewp-voilealluremarineleventarrière-e-3ffa3208:: [html]What is observed on a running point of sail (dead downwind)? {
=Rolling increases and an (accidental) gybe threatens
~Speed becomes maximal, higher than on a broad reach
~The sailboat can no longer make headway because it is head to wind
####[html]On a run the airflow over the sails is disturbed\: speed drops compared with a broad reach, rolling increases and an accidental gybe threatens.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allure_(marine)">Voile — Allure (marine) \: Le vent arrière — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (223790627)</a>
}

::q-voilewp-voilealluremarineleventdebout-b2-13f2a3f2:: [html]On the head-to-wind point of sail, what must the sailboat do to make headway under sail? {
=Bear away about 45° from the wind axis (30° on the highest-performance racing yachts)
~Hold its course exactly head to wind, sheeting its sails in fully
~Set the spinnaker to catch the wind coming from ahead
####[html]Head to wind the sailboat cannot make headway\: it must bear away about 45° from the wind axis (30° in racing) and beat to windward (tack).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allure_(marine)">Voile — Allure (marine) \: Le vent debout — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (223790627)</a>
}

::q-voilewp-voilealluremarinetribordamuresbâ-dfe53188:: [html]When is a sailboat said to be «on starboard tack»? {
=When the wind comes from the right relative to the boat's axis
~When it sails downwind with the sails wing-on-wing (in scissors)
~When it has right of way over every other boat on the water
####[html]A sailboat is on starboard tack when the wind comes from the right (starboard), and on port tack in the opposite case. These distinctions underlie the right-of-way rules between sailboats.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allure_(marine)">Voile — Allure (marine) \: Tribord amures, bâbord amures — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (223790627)</a>
}

::q-voilewp-voilechaviragesourceduphénomène--afe43868:: [html]On a light sport dinghy, what is a capsize commonly called and what is its nature? {
=A «capsize»\: it is common and harmless
~A «shipwreck»\: it almost always leads to the loss of the boat
~A «rounding up»\: it occurs only when close-hauled
####[html]On a light dinghy the capsize is common and harmless; it results from seeking excessive speed or from poor crew placement.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chavirage">Voile — Chavirage \: Source du phénomène — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (231891130)</a>
}

::q-voilewp-voileempannagedéfinition-34dc964-475707cc:: [html]What characterises the gybe (empannage) compared with tacking? {
=The change of tack is made by passing through the wind astern (downwind)
~The change of tack is made by passing head to wind
~It does not change the set of the sails
####[html]A gybe changes tack by passing through the wind astern (downwind); passing head to wind is instead a tack (virement de bord).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empannage">Voile — Empannage \: Définition — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (236265378)</a>
}

::q-voilewp-voilefocprésentation-30eec01b-ee50d7a3:: [html]What is the jib on a sailboat? {
=A triangular headsail, held to the forestay (stay) by its luff
~The mainsail, rigged abaft the mast
~A standing-rigging wire that holds the mast up
####[html]The jib is a triangular headsail held to the stay by its luff; it plays a key role in the success of the tack.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foc">Voile — Foc \: Présentation — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (227846382)</a>
}

::q-voilewp-voilevirementdebordprincipe-90e4-40419c62:: [html]What happens during a tack (virement de bord)? {
=The side of the boat that was leeward becomes windward, and vice versa
~The sailboat keeps the same tack throughout the manoeuvre
~The manoeuvre is necessarily made by passing through the wind astern
####[html]In a tack, the side that was leeward becomes windward (a change of tack made by passing head to wind).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virement_de_bord">Voile — Virement de bord \: Principe — Wikipédia (FR) — navigation à voile (technique) (220344446)</a>
}
